@node "Troubleshooting"
@title "HELP!!  I can't get AmiTALK to work!!"

@{fg fill}@{b} Problem:@{ub}  @{fg text}I don't get notified of incoming talk requests.@{fg text}

@{fg shine}@{b}Solution:@{ub}  @{fg text}There are two solutions to this:

	   1)  Get @{b}RexxReqTools1_3.lha@{ub} from @{"aminet" LINK "aminet"} in util/rexx.

	   2)  Get KS 3.0 or higher and copy 30talkrequest.rx to
	       amitcp:bin/talkrequest.rx.

	   3)  Write an amitcp:bin/talkrequest.rx that uses neither KS 3.0 nor rexxreqtools.
	       Once you have done this, mail it to me so I can include it in the next release.

@{fg fill}@{b} Problem:@{ub}  @{fg text}When I run talk, I get a "Couldn't get a username.
	   Have you logged in?" error.

@{fg shine}@{b}Solution:@{ub}  @{fg text}Run the AmiTCP "login" command to login to AmiTCP.
	   If you cannot figure out how to login,then run:

	   setenv USER @{i}<username>@{ui}

	   from the amiga shell (where @{i}<username>@{ui} is your login name).

	   @{u}Example:@{uu}

	   @{b}Preferred method:@{ub}

	   	login -f gunnbr

	   @{b}Non-preferred method:@{ub}

	   	setenv USER gunnbr

@{fg fill}@{b} Problem:@{ub}  @{fg text}When I run talk, I get a "Couldn't bind to control socket" error.

@{fg shine}@{b}Solution:@{ub}  @{fg text}Unfortunately, I know of no solution to this.  I do not get this
	   error on any machine I have physical access to, so I am having
	   difficulty debugging it.

	   As of this this release, I am including a script (called 
	   @{fg shine}DebugInformation@{fg text}) that will help me determine the cause of the 
	   problem.  Please run this and email the results to me.

@{fg fill}@{b} Problem:@{ub}  @{fg text}I can't answer incoming talk requests.@{fg text}

@{fg shine}@{b}Solution:@{ub}  @{fg text}Someone is being paged other than the person currently logged in.
	   This will be fixed in the future such that if a person other than
	   the one currently logged in is paged, AmiTALK will return a "Your
	   party is not logged on" message.

@{fg fill}@{b} Problem:@{ub}  @{fg text}Talk locks up when run.@{fg text}

@{fg shine}@{b}Solution:@{ub}  @{fg text}Well, I'm sure there are many reasons this could happen.  The one I
	   am aware of is that if the environment variable USER has a
	   linefeed in it, talk will lock up (on a printf I believe).
	   I am investigating this problem.

@{fg fill}@{b} Problem:@{ub}  @{fg text}AmiTALK simply doesn't work.@{fg text}

@{fg shine}@{b}Solution:@{ub}  @{fg text}There are many different versions of talk floating around the net.
	   Not all these versions of talk are compatible.  It could be that the version
	   of talk you are using is not compatible with AmiTALK.  Try a different version
	   of talk on the remote machine.

@{fg fill}@{b} Problem:@{ub}  @{fg text}I don't get talk requesters.@{fg text}

@{fg shine}@{b}Solution:@{ub}  @{fg text}Make sure the command @{b}rx@{ub} is in your default system path.

@{i}Return to @{ui}@{"main" LINK "main"}.

@endnode

@Node "aminet"
@title "Aminet mirror sites"

From the Aminet README:

5. Mirror sites
---------------

These are the members of Aminet and have the files from here.  All mirrors
have the new files but most delete old files, however ftp.wustl.edu,
ftp.uni-paderborn.de and ftp.doc.ic.ac.uk  keep all files.  Whenever
possible, use the mirror that is the closest to your place.  Most mirrors
get updated three times a day.

